      "callEndedTimestamp": null,
      "isPinned": false,
      "content": "Thanks for the responses! I should clarify a bit what I'm trying to do. I'm exploring using snarkyJS and recursive ZKs to create an alternative to permissioned/consortium blockchains.\n\nThe insight I'm borrowing from Mina Protocol is that recursive ZKs have similar properties to blockchains in that they can be used to verify a series of state changes (correct me if I'm wrong here, but this seems implicit in the design of ZKProgram.)\n\nPermissioned blockchains are a very bad solution to the problem of enterprises who want to have truthful data but want to hide this data from the world. They are a web2 \"if we wall in this garden\" we're safe kind of solution.\n\nMy thinking is what if you could use recursive ZKs to allow users to spin up a \"mini-blockchain\" around a single business process. Like say a single document you need to get a bunch of signatures on... you create this \"mini-blockchain\" and then just pass it around to all the people who need to sign. Nobody else needs to touch this data so let's not mix it all together in a public or even permissioned blockchain.\n\nSo this is why I'm trying to limit state on the blockchain to just cryptographic commitments. All other state lives as the public inputs to the recursive ZKs. Nothing needs to happen on-chain, but using the chain to verify that data is accurate.\n\nDoes this make sense or am I smoking something funky?",
      "author": {
        "id": "719523315815022613",
        "name": "jierenchen",
        "discriminator": "0000",
        "nickname": "jierenchen",
